a 14 meert 1682
Eeon mr. Witt. Hobb
mij last to you was on the 11th cur. when desired you to provide for mee 12 drap cullouns, en
sparrow grays cloth serges 22 yd & of al most ayd. broad with 6 or 8 fine 24 yd senges
to then you might add 10 gold & blanck mixt cloth serges as browne as possible as the first
you sent mee, to be one bale in all that is, provided itt could be ready to come either by
John Ewincx or wills now in loading with you for ostend or Bruges, which I hope you shall
be able to effect. now have before mee yd of 25 past with pattarnes & invoyce of a bale
M.N.S. aboard John Ewings the contents I finde 30 mixt serges att 43 Æ a 5 raw hine
that must be a mistake, for I never had any grayes of such a rate, I supose you meane
43 Æ face, from all charges a board or elces I shall certainly loose by thene amonghst
the charges is no provision included neither I have goods from other freindes that promises
as well bij the patt. as yd butt in prijse no grayes above 39 Æ 40 the sparrow gray es
& the gold cullours 42,so I do wonder yd. be all 43 as will grayes as others, except you
rekon them all att that rate face, aboard, after this rate I doubt I shall not finde
incorridgment to leave my old way, yett I must see the goods though yett nevrhadd
on saw any 22 yd serges grayes att 43 Æ a 9. raw, I exspect yd answer & shall
either remitt you, or order you to draw
a 14 meert 1682 144
Lenden m. Abram Vivian
On the 25th past, desired you to inorder a bale of fijne broad cloathes from the north, which I
hope you have don accordingly, though I can not butt wonder to finde no letters from you
so that I am altoghether in the darck how our concernes go on in the north, yett I hope
there is nothing omitted to send mee the bayes by finst vessel. pray lett mee heare from
you, & have yd approbation of the actt sent, as also my cctt. curtt. to see if wee do aggrie
besides in case you do not come over, so please to advise mee yd minde, if you will
proued in our trade, or desist, for time drawnes vere neare that wee must be bussye du
the north, & if you will neglect itt, I not, butt whoever lett mee know how to take mys
measures, for I can not a bide to come after the fare, so in exspectation of yd answer
a 14d
Londen mr. Picheringh & Robbinson
In antwer to yd of 24 pass do daylay endeavour all I can to dispose of our northrers, butt
I doubt I shall be forced to banter them with tijkes, because I finde they do not amend
by lying to the walles, & yett they are badd goods, that in conscience I never had the
like, yd bill on louis collage is accepted & where payd shall be past to yd credit you also
complaine of the tykes, butt how shall I help , I finde that wee must desist in all
for never in this world went things so badd, as how they do here, there is neither trade
nor mony, & yett the countrey menaced with a furious warr, besides the lamentable iindation
happyned in Jan. Case, patience, where in I can be servicable unto you, or any other freind
truly commande

verwaghte. voorders hebbe nogh eene groote partije puijcq nieuw daet van doen
soo gelieft ul morgen niet 't convoij van Tempst eens over te comen, ul can op
eenen dagh wederom t' huys sijn, alsoo het goet getey is, ende wij sullen dan mondeiug
alles ordineeren, want ick vreese dat ul mijn order niet wel en verstaet, daer
